00:36:52.180 --> 00:36:56.880
I'm curious whether after
the initial sort of success

00:36:56.880 --> 00:36:58.890
of settling in the
Americas, was that sort

00:36:58.890 --> 00:37:01.260
of like a huge bubble--

00:37:01.260 --> 00:37:03.480
you know, an America bubble
which eventually burst?

00:37:03.480 --> 00:37:06.570
And how did sort of the
ongoing investment dynamic

00:37:06.570 --> 00:37:10.022
work after the initial
settlement and you know,

00:37:10.022 --> 00:37:12.230
leading I guess, all the
way to the Revolutionary War

00:37:12.230 --> 00:37:14.025
where I guess things
were disrupted?

00:37:14.025 --> 00:37:15.774
JOHN BUTMAN: Yeah, so
two things happened.

00:37:15.774 --> 00:37:19.920
One is that after the pilgrims
and after Jamestown found

00:37:19.920 --> 00:37:23.490
tobacco, which was
their big product,

00:37:23.490 --> 00:37:26.050
there was a bubble
of colonial activity

00:37:26.050 --> 00:37:28.650
and not just from the English,
but also from the French

00:37:28.650 --> 00:37:29.940
and from the Dutch.

00:37:29.940 --> 00:37:32.640
So you see the Dutch in New
York and you see the French

00:37:32.640 --> 00:37:33.732
in Canada.

00:37:33.732 --> 00:37:35.190
And suddenly, all
these settlements

00:37:35.190 --> 00:37:36.450
are coming in to New England.

00:37:36.450 --> 00:37:37.860
So there's a lot of activity.

00:37:37.860 --> 00:37:41.310
And the Pilgrims figured
out how to do fur trade.

00:37:41.310 --> 00:37:42.630
So they were sustainable.

00:37:42.630 --> 00:37:45.570
They didn't make a lot of money
but they were sustainable.

00:37:45.570 --> 00:37:49.020
So yeah, suddenly
it was possible.

00:37:49.020 --> 00:37:50.170
They knew how to do it.

00:37:50.170 --> 00:37:51.253
They knew what you needed.

00:37:51.253 --> 00:37:53.760
They knew how many people
you needed, how much money.

00:37:53.760 --> 00:37:56.075
They figured out the
sort of fur trade

00:37:56.075 --> 00:37:57.450
and they had a
lot of other ideas

00:37:57.450 --> 00:38:01.344
for commerce that didn't work
out but fur was the basic one.

00:38:01.344 --> 00:38:02.760
And they also went
back to fishing

00:38:02.760 --> 00:38:04.260
because fishing was
a very reliable.

00:38:04.260 --> 00:38:07.300
Fishing was great in New
England, especially in Maine.

00:38:07.300 --> 00:38:09.280
So that's one thing.

00:38:09.280 --> 00:38:12.090
But they also eventually
made it to the Far East.

00:38:12.090 --> 00:38:14.590
So you see the English
starting to trade

00:38:14.590 --> 00:38:15.660
to get to the Far East.

00:38:15.660 --> 00:38:18.490
So now you've got
another source of income.

00:38:18.490 --> 00:38:22.140
So the investors put together
basically a portfolio

00:38:22.140 --> 00:38:22.730
of investment.

00:38:22.730 --> 00:38:25.206
So they've got some
investments in America,

00:38:25.206 --> 00:38:27.330
they've got some investments
in the Far East trade.

00:38:30.090 --> 00:38:33.140
They're still selling in
to the continental markets

00:38:33.140 --> 00:38:34.860
and they probably
own some fishing.

00:38:34.860 --> 00:38:37.210
So they put together a
series of investments.

00:38:37.210 --> 00:38:39.330
Some are high risk and
some are not so high risk.

00:38:39.330 --> 00:38:41.070
So yeah, they start
to make money.

00:38:41.070 --> 00:38:45.370
But the early ones really did
not make any money at all.

00:38:45.370 --> 00:38:48.150
AUDIENCE: Do you think that
they'll ever sort of rewrite

00:38:48.150 --> 00:38:52.390
the story of the Pilgrims so
that we can get it correct

00:38:52.390 --> 00:38:53.715
and teach it correctly?

00:38:53.715 --> 00:38:55.090
JOHN BUTMAN: Teach
our children--

00:38:55.090 --> 00:38:55.720
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:38:55.720 --> 00:38:56.940
JOHN BUTMAN: --well?

00:38:56.940 --> 00:39:01.290
Well, that's our plan for
that our next book actually.

00:39:01.290 --> 00:39:05.185
It's funny because the
literature about the Pilgrims

00:39:05.185 --> 00:39:06.060
is quite interesting.

00:39:06.060 --> 00:39:08.820
So the most recent one
is Nathaniel Philbrick

00:39:08.820 --> 00:39:10.770
wrote a book called "Mayflower."

00:39:10.770 --> 00:39:14.910
And he takes the
Pilgrims from 1620 up

00:39:14.910 --> 00:39:18.540
through the King Philip's
War, which is 1675.

00:39:18.540 --> 00:39:21.840
But he basically retells
the story as they told it.

00:39:21.840 --> 00:39:24.670
Just saying this part of
it isn't so well known.

00:39:24.670 --> 00:39:30.350
He doesn't really sort of
reframe it the way we have.

00:39:30.350 --> 00:39:34.810
So it's interesting
because over the years,

00:39:34.810 --> 00:39:36.914
especially in this
19th century period,

00:39:36.914 --> 00:39:39.330
Pilgrims have become the vessel
to be filled with whatever

00:39:39.330 --> 00:39:41.570
story you want to tell.

00:39:41.570 --> 00:39:43.980
But I think it's really
important to retell it now

00:39:43.980 --> 00:39:46.560
in this way because, to
me, it says a lot about how

00:39:46.560 --> 00:39:48.130
we got to where we are.

00:39:48.130 --> 00:39:50.130
So that's what we're
going to try to do, yeah.

00:39:50.130 --> 00:39:51.630
AUDIENCE: There's
another thing that

00:39:51.630 --> 00:39:55.620
struck me reading the book
is that this took generations

00:39:55.620 --> 00:40:01.070
and it could have happened
almost 100 years earlier

00:40:01.070 --> 00:40:03.122
with the right people and so on.

00:40:03.122 --> 00:40:04.830
Do you think that's
true or did it really

00:40:04.830 --> 00:40:07.485
need to take that long?

00:40:07.485 --> 00:40:10.110
JOHN BUTMAN: Well, it certainly
could of because of the Spanish

00:40:10.110 --> 00:40:13.290
were in the West Indies from
the beginning of you know,

00:40:13.290 --> 00:40:15.600
1512 they go in to Mexico.

00:40:15.600 --> 00:40:17.100
So it certainly
could have happened.

00:40:17.100 --> 00:40:18.850
But the Spanish are
much better sea-goers.

00:40:18.850 --> 00:40:22.860
They had better ships and they
had a very different attitude.

00:40:22.860 --> 00:40:26.850
So it's the whole
big discussion here

00:40:26.850 --> 00:40:31.950
is the relationship of Europeans
to local indigenous cultures.

00:40:31.950 --> 00:40:36.240
And the Spanish basically just
went in and marauded and killed

00:40:36.240 --> 00:40:40.470
and subjugated and took over
in the West Indies and Mexico

00:40:40.470 --> 00:40:41.910
and South America.

00:40:41.910 --> 00:40:44.160
And the English very,
very consciously

00:40:44.160 --> 00:40:46.350
said, we don't want
to do it that way.

00:40:46.350 --> 00:40:47.670
We want to behave differently.

00:40:47.670 --> 00:40:50.460
And in fact, in his
early years, they did.

00:40:50.460 --> 00:40:54.860
And although they did
kidnap Inuits and Indians

00:40:54.860 --> 00:40:57.770
and bring them back
to England, they also

00:40:57.770 --> 00:40:59.760
returned them to America.

00:40:59.760 --> 00:41:02.720
And the relationship
was very different.

00:41:02.720 --> 00:41:05.620
And they didn't really
have this religious purpose

00:41:05.620 --> 00:41:07.500
that the Spanish had.

00:41:07.500 --> 00:41:10.080
So yeah, it could
have been done.

00:41:10.080 --> 00:41:13.410
But England was just-- they
were just really far behind.

00:41:13.410 --> 00:41:15.690
Something about
England just hadn't

00:41:15.690 --> 00:41:20.402
gotten there yet whereas the
Portuguese and the Spanish had.

00:41:20.402 --> 00:41:21.360
But there's no reason--

00:41:21.360 --> 00:41:23.390
I mean, America yeah, there's
no reason they couldn't have.

00:41:23.390 --> 00:41:24.510
AUDIENCE: Of course
one could also

00:41:24.510 --> 00:41:26.280
argue that the Spanish
and the Portuguese

00:41:26.280 --> 00:41:29.040
did have one of those rare
get rich quick successes.

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:30.981
There was gold lying around.

00:41:30.981 --> 00:41:31.730
JOHN BUTMAN: Yeah.

00:41:31.730 --> 00:41:32.460
AUDIENCE: It might have--

00:41:32.460 --> 00:41:34.418
JOHN BUTMAN: What's
intriguing though is if you

00:41:34.418 --> 00:41:37.090
read about how it turned out--

00:41:37.090 --> 00:41:40.830
in fact, having this enormous
stream of gold and silver

00:41:40.830 --> 00:41:44.670
coming into Spain
ruined them basically.

00:41:44.670 --> 00:41:50.070
Because King Philip said I
can prosecute any war I want.

00:41:50.070 --> 00:41:51.870
I can do anything I want to.

00:41:51.870 --> 00:41:53.380
Spent lots and lots of money--

00:41:53.380 --> 00:41:56.250
they actually declared
bankruptcy at one point.

00:41:56.250 --> 00:41:59.010
And it didn't do them
any good in the long run.

00:41:59.010 --> 00:42:01.110
And the English--
it was good in a way

00:42:01.110 --> 00:42:04.800
that they saw this example
and that they once sort of

00:42:04.800 --> 00:42:07.240
said, let's go get this
gold mine didn't work.

00:42:07.240 --> 00:42:09.827
And then they sort of
focused on other things.

00:42:09.827 --> 00:42:10.660
Thank you very much.

00:42:10.660 --> 00:42:11.410
Thanks for coming.

00:42:11.410 --> 00:42:14.450
[APPLAUSE]

